{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}} {{Infobox galaxy cluster | name = Abell 223 | image = | caption = | credit = | epoch = [[J2000]] | constellation = [[Cetus]] | ra = {{RA|01|37|55.9}}<ref name=SIMBAD>{{cite simbad|title=ACO 223|access-date=26 November 2017}}</ref> | dec = {{DEC|-12|49|11}}<ref name=SIMBAD/> | brightest_member = LEDA 947139<ref>{{cite simbad|title=2MASX J01375602-1249106|access-date=26 November 2017}}</ref> | member_no = | richness = 3<ref name=ACO>{{cite journal|last1=Abell|first1=George O.|last2=Corwin|first2=Harold G., Jr.|last3=Olowin|first3=Ronald P.|date=May 1989|title=A catalog of rich clusters of galaxies|journal=Astrophysical Journal Supplement Series|volume=70|issue=May 1989|pages=1–138|format=PDF|issn=0067-0049|bibcode=1989ApJS...70....1A|doi=10.1086/191333}}</ref> | bmtype = III<ref name=ACO/> | velocity_dispersion = 1032 km/s<ref name=Durret/> | redshift = 0.2079 ± 0.0008<ref name=Durret/> | distance = {{convert|2.4|Mly|Mpc|abbr=on|lk=on}}<ref name=csmonitor/> <!-- {{hub|0.00}} --> | temperature = 4.38 ± 0.16<ref name=Durret>{{cite journal|doi=10.1051/0004-6361/201014566|title=The clusters Abell 222 and Abell 223: A multi-wavelength view|journal=Astronomy and Astrophysics|volume=517|pages=A94|year=2010|last1=Durret|first1=F|last2=Laganá|first2=T. F|last3=Adami|first3=C|last4=Bertin|first4=E|bibcode=2010A&A...517A..94D|arxiv=1005.3295}}</ref><!-- kT --> | mass = <!-- 0{{e|14}} {{hub|0.00}} In solar masses --> | luminosity = | flux = | other_names = RXC J0137.9-1248<ref name=SIMBAD/> }} '''Abell 223''' is a [[galaxy cluster]]. It is located at a distance of 2.4 billion light-years from [[Earth]]. The cluster is connected to nearby cluster Abell 222 by a filament of matter. Research has shown that only 20% of that matter is normal. The rest is thought to be dark matter.<ref name=csmonitor>{{cite web |url=http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2012/0705/Cosmic-scaffolding-uncovered-Scientists-find-thread-of-dark-matter |title=Cosmic scaffolding uncovered? Scientists find thread of dark matter. |author=Pete Spotts |date=5 July 2012|accessdate= 14 July 2012|work=[[The Christian Science Monitor]]|publisher=[[Christian Science Publishing Society]]}}</ref>
