{{astronomy-stub}}

The '''Injun''' program was a series of six [[satellite]]s designed and built by researchers at the [[University of Iowa]]. They were intended to observe various radiation and magnetic phenomena in the [[ionosphere]] and beyond.
The design specifics of the satellites had little in common, though all were solar-powered and the first five used [[Magnetorquer|magnetic stabilization]] to control spacecraft attitude. (The last in the series was spin-stabilized.) Instruments included particle detectors of varying types, [[magnetometer]]s, and [[photometer]]s for observing [[aurora (astronomy)|aurora]]s.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Swift, Daniel W.|author2=Gurnett, Donald A.|title=Direct comparison between satellite electric field measurements and the visual aurora|journal=Research Report|date=1973|publisher=University of Iowa, Department of Physics and Astronomy|location=Iowa City, Iowa}}</ref> The last three satellites were launched as part of the [[Explorer program]].
In spite of various hardware difficulties and the loss of Injun 2 due to an upper stage failure, the program was generally successful. In particular they produced data on the [[Van_Allen_radiation_belt|Van Allen radiation belts]] including [[Magnetospheric electric convection field|electrical convection in the magnetosphere]]<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gurnett|first1=Donald|editor1-last=Dyer|editor1-first=E.R.|title=Electrical Fields and Plasma Observations in the Magnetosphere, in Critical Problems in Magnetospheric Physics|publisher=American Geophyscial Union|location=Washington, D.C.|pages=123–138|url=http://www-pw.physics.uiowa.edu/~dag/publications/1972_ElectricFieldAndPlasmaObservationsInMagnetosphere_AGU-BOOK.pdf|accessdate=8 February 2015}}</ref> and the radiation after effects of the [[Starfish Prime]] [[high altitude nuclear explosion|high-altitude nuclear test]].<ref>{{cite journal | first = Wilmot N. | last = Hess | authorlink = Wilmot N. Hess | title = The Effects of High Altitude Explosions | publisher = [[National Aeronautics and Space Administration]] | date = September 1964 | url = https://ntrs.nasa.gov/archive/nasa/casi.ntrs.nasa.gov/19640018807_1964018807.pdf | format = [[PDF]] | id = NASA TN D-2402 | accessdate = 2007-10-07 }}</ref>
